article.description: Lauren Jackson had 16 points and 12 rebounds and Sherri Sam added 15 points and seven rebounds to lead the WNBA-leading Seattle Storm to an 86-62 victory Tuesday night over the slumping New York Liberty.
article.headline: Seattle pulls away before the half, rolls
article.linkText: Jackson paces first-place Storm over Liberty
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The Seattle Storm recovered from a slow start
and rolled past the New York Liberty.

Lauren Jackson led four Seattle scorers in double figures with
16 points and 12 rebounds, and the WNBA-leading Storm won their
fourth straight with an 86-62 victory against the slumping New York
Liberty on Tuesday night.

Seattle used a 41-12 run over a 15-minute stretch spanning
halftime to take a 23-point lead and hand New York its third
straight loss after a six-game winning streak.

"The end of the first half really carried us," Seattle coach
Anne Donovan said. "Gave us the momentum going into halftime. They
looked fatigued in the second half. A lot of their shots were short
and I think that was a result of our defense."

Sherri Sam had 15 points and seven rebounds, Janell Burse 12
points and nine rebounds and Betty Lennox added 10 points and six
rebounds for Seattle. After committing seven turnovers in the first
15 minutes, the Storm had just two the rest of the way.

The Liberty matched their second-worst loss in franchise
history, topped only by a 79-54 setback against Houston on July 18,
1998. New York also had a 24-point loss in last season's opener at
Cleveland.

"This was embarassing," Liberty coach Richie Adubato said.
"We'll need to make some adjustments. We're going to watch this
game together as a team, and work to regroup."

Ann Wauters had 15 points and five rebounds, Crystal Robinson
had 13 points, and Elena Baranova added 12 points and five rebounds
for the Liberty.

Seattle closed the first half with a 17-6 run over the final
4:25 to take a 37-32 lead at the intermission. Lennox had eight
points during the run, and Jackson had six.

"We felt there was an advantage there with Betty over Becky
(Hammon), and we kept running the same play," Donovan said. "That
was a huge surge for us. A big confidence boost for everybody.

The Storm picked up where they left off in the second half,
outscoring the Liberty 24-6 over the first 10{ minutes to take a
61-38 lead. Seattle led by at least 21 the rest of the way and had
its biggest lead at 81-54 with just under two minutes remaining.

The Storm shot 44 percent from the field and had 19 offensive
rebounds while finishing with a 44-26 edge overall on the boards.

"We cannot give up 19 offensive rebounds and expect to win,"
Robinson said. "Everyone on the team has to take the
responsibility of rebounding, and we need to work on boxing out."

Seattle split its first four road games this season after losing
12 of 17 last year.

"It's been our focus to take care of the road," Donovan said.
"We feel two of the hardest places to play are Madison Square
Garden and Arco Arena. Those are two wins we already have under our
belt."

New York shot 36.5 percent, including 13.3 percent (2-for-15) on
3-pointers.
